The key insight in this solution is to use the distributive property to simplify the calculation. By distributing the multiplication of 6 over the sum of 8 and $\frac{1}{3}$, we can avoid having to convert the mixed number $8\frac{1}{3}$ into an improper fraction. This approach makes the calculation more straightforward and easier to solve.
1. Apply the distributive property to rewrite the expression:
   $$\begin{align*}
   6 \cdot 8\frac{1}{3} &= 6 \cdot \left(8 + \frac{1}{3}\right)
   \end{align*}$$

2. Multiply 6 by 8 and simplify:
   $$\begin{align*}
   6 \cdot \left(8 + \frac{1}{3}\right) &= 48 + 6 \cdot\frac{1}{3}
   \end{align*}$$

3. Multiply 6 by $\frac{1}{3}$:
   $$\begin{align*}
   48 + 6 \cdot\frac{1}{3} &= 48 + \frac{6}{3}
   \end{align*}$$

4. Simplify the fraction:
   $$\begin{align*}
   48 + \frac{6}{3} &= 48 + 2
   \end{align*}$$

5. Add the whole numbers:
   $$\begin{align*}
   48 + 2 &= 50
   \end{align*}$$
$6 \cdot 8\frac{1}{3} = \boxed{50}$

